#, no-wrap
msgid "SELinux security"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:13
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the arrival of kernel version 2.6, a new security system was introduced to provide a security mechanism to support access control security policies.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "This system is called **SELinux** (**S**ecurity **E**nhanced **Linux**) and was created by the **NSA** (**N**ational **S**ecurity **A**gency) to implement a robust **M**andatory **A**ccess **C**ontrol (**MAC**) architecture in the Linux kernel subsystems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "If, throughout your career, you have either disabled or ignored SELinux, this document will be a good introduction to this system. SELinux works to limit privileges or remove the risks associated with compromising a program or daemon.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "Before starting, you should know that SELinux is mainly intended for RHEL distributions, although it is possible to implement it on other distributions like Debian (but good luck!). The distributions of the Debian family generally integrate the AppArmor system, which works differently from SELinux.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "**SELinux** (Security Enhanced Linux) is a Mandatory Access Control system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:25
#, no-wrap
msgid "Before the appearance of MAC systems, standard access management security was based on **DAC** (**D**iscretionary **A**ccess **C**ontrol) systems. An application, or a daemon, operated with **UID** or **SUID** (**S**et **O**wner **U**ser **I**d) rights, which made it possible to evaluate permissions (on files, sockets, and other processes...) according to this user. This operation does not sufficiently limit the rights of a program that is corrupted, potentially allowing it to access the subsystems of the operating system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "A MAC system reinforces the separation of confidentiality and integrity information in the system to achieve a containment system. The containment system is independent of the traditional rights system and there is no notion of a superuser.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "With each system call, the kernel queries SELinux to see if it allows the action to be performed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "![SELinux](../images/selinux_001.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "SELinux uses a set of rules (policies) for this. A set of two standard rule sets (**targeted** and **strict**) is provided and each application usually provides its own rules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "The SELinux context"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "The operation of SELinux is totally different from traditional Unix rights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "The SELinux security context is defined by the trio **identity**+**role**+**domain**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "The identity of a user depends directly on his Linux account. An identity is assigned one or more roles, but to each role corresponds to one domain, and only one.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is according to the domain of the security context (and thus the role) that the rights of a user on a resource are evaluated.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "![SELinux context](../images/selinux_002.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "The terms \"domain\" and \"type\" are similar. Typically \"domain\" is used when referring to a process, while \"type\" refers to an object.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "The naming convention is: **user_u:role_r:type_t**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "The security context is assigned to a user at the time of his connection, according to his roles. The security context of a file is defined by the `chcon` (**ch**ange **con**text) command, which we will see later in this document.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "Consider the following pieces of the SELinux puzzle:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "The subjects\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "The objects\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "The policies\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "The mode\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "When a subject (an application for example) tries to access an object (a file for example), the SELinux part of the Linux kernel queries its policy database. Depending on the mode of operation, SELinux authorizes access to the object in case of success, otherwise it records the failure in the file `/var/log/messages`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "The SELinux context of standard processes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "The rights of a process depend on its security context.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, the security context of the process is defined by the context of the user (identity + role + domain) who launches it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "A domain being a specific type (in the SELinux sense) linked to a process and inherited (normally) from the user who launched it, its rights are expressed in terms of authorization or refusal on types linked to objects:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "A process whose context has security __domain D__ can access objects of __type T__.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "![The SELinux context of standard processes](../images/selinux_003.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "The SELinux context of important processes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:76
#, no-wrap
msgid "Most important programs are assigned a dedicated domain.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each executable is tagged with a dedicated type (here **sshd_exec_t**) which automatically switches the associated process to the **sshd_t** context (instead of **user_t**).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "This mechanism is essential since it restricts the rights of a process as much as possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/learning_selinux.md:82
#, no-wrap
